Chicago July 20 1888

Mr B. Stone Esq
General Manager BR2 RR City
Dear Sir:
Following please find report of Operation D.D.
Saturday July 14'88
To-day at National Hotel.
There were a great many callers to-day to see  (([Hage?})) and Murphy and among them was Bowles' Brother who had a long consultation with Roger in the Hall near Hage's room.  J.J Bowles comes from Logansport Indiana they are all very bitter against the U.S Commissioner in the way they claim he ruled against them there were several (([junknown])) few were here who seem to take great interest in the trial and who are very bitter against Kelley and all who are reported to have made confessions -after the trial before the Commissioner Hages' room was crowded with them all expressing their opinion as to the result

of the trial a man named David who comes from (([unknown})) saying Boys now is the time to stick, for if your weaker now we are gone, when Hage spoke and said, you fellows must not talk around in the office or on the street as Stone has his hired sons of B- every where as you can see and the less you talk the better it will be for all of us- Kennedy came to see Hage at this time when they retired for a private consultation which lasted for about half an hour.  I could not hear their conversation but think it was in reference to Fowler as Hage said to Kennedy when he was leaving with him that he had better stay where he is for the present, they had expected Fowler this morning, but he did not come.  Murphy received a letter from Thomas, saying the boys are wild about these arrests and there will be trouble now - Murphy was reading this letter to three or four in his room; Kennedy has been in and out of Hages' room a great many times this evening holding short talks with Hage, them leaving and returning this eve about 10pm two were given cause to see Hage.
